backend-tbd — Handover & API Documentation

1 — Executive summary
This is a Node.js + Express backend for an assessment platform. It provides:

- User authentication & profile management (admins, leaders, managers, employees).
- Invitation-based employee flows (tokenized no-login access).
- Assessment lifecycle: create/start assessments, collect responses, export reports.
- Question bank CRUD and bulk-upload via Excel.
- Dashboards and role-based intelligence reports (PDF/Excel exports).
- File uploads (images, Excel), email sending, and a small cron job for cleanup.

Primary audience: the next backend engineer or maintainer taking over the product.

2 — Stack & notable libraries
- Language: JavaScript (ES modules; package.json "type":"module")
- Runtime / Framework: Node.js + Express (express v5)
- Database: MongoDB via mongoose
- Scheduler: node-cron
- File upload: multer (disk storage)
- Email: nodemailer / @sendgrid/mail / resend (repo contains several email libraries; check controllers for which is used)
- Excel/CSV: exceljs, csv-parser, xlsx, json2xls
- PDF/HTML: puppeteer / @sparticuz/chromium, pdf-lib
- Image handling: sharp, cloudinary
- Auth: jsonwebtoken

3 — Repo layout (top-level)
- src/
  - config/ env loader
  - db/ mongoose connection (connectDB)
  - controllers/ HTTP handlers (business logic)
  - middlewares/ auth, employeeAccess, file uploads, roles
  - models/ mongoose models (User, Invitation, Question, Response, etc)
  - routes/ route definitions (auth, assessment, questions, responses, dashboard, organization, contact, employeeAssessment)
  - services/ (helper/service code — check folder)
  - utils/ utility helpers
  - src/index.js server start + cron + index cleanup
  - src/app.js express app, global middlewares, route mounting
- package.json scripts & dependencies
- README.md
- Dockerfile
- public/

How it fits together
- src/index.js imports env, connects to DB, possibly starts server and schedules cron.
- src/app.js builds the Express app, sets global middleware (DB connect on each req for serverless safety), mounts route modules under /api/v1/* and exports app.
- Controllers contain request validation, DB operations using models, and third-party calls (email, cloudinary, puppeteer).
- Middlewares handle JWT auth, invitation tokens, role restrictions and file uploads.

4 — How to run locally (quick start)
- Copy .env.example -> .env and fill required values (MONGODB_URL, JWT_SECRET, etc).
- Install:
  npm install
- Start development server:
  npm run dev (dev uses nodemon with dotenv)
- Start production-like server:
  npm start
- Health check:
  GET http://localhost:8000/ -> { success: true, message: "API is working 🚀" }

Important script names (package.json)
- start: node src/index.js
- dev: nodemon -r dotenv/config src/index.js
- lint: eslint

5 — Environment variables (required / recommended)
Core:
- MONGODB_URL — MongoDB connection string (required)
- JWT_SECRET — secret for signing JWTs (required)
- NODE_ENV — development | production
- PORT — port to run server (default 8000)
- VERCEL — if set, index.js will NOT start the server (used to run on Vercel)

CORS / frontend:
- CORS_ORIGIN or FRONTEND_URL — frontend URL used by app.js

Email / file storage (examples; check controllers):
- SENDGRID_API_KEY, RESEND_API_KEY, SMTP_* — email sending credentials
- CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME, CLOUDINARY_API_KEY, CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET — cloudinary credentials

Suggested: add .env.example in repo (see previous message for example template).

6 — DB & models summary (main documents)
All models are in src/models/*.model.js. Key ones:

User (src/models/user.model.js)
- Fields: email (unique), password, role (superAdmin|admin|leader|manager|employee), orgName, adminId, firstName/lastName, department, profileImage, isEmailVerified, emailVerificationToken/expires, resetPasswordToken/expires, invitationToken, profileCompleted flags, notificationPreferences, lastAssessmentScore/classification.
- Methods: generateAccessToken() -> signs JWT (expiresIn: 3h).
- Indexes: invitationToken, orgName+role, role, emailVerificationToken, resetPasswordToken.

Invitation (src/models/invitation.model.js)
- Stores invitation tokens, invited email, invitedBy, orgName, role, department, used flag, expiredAt.
- Used for employeeAccess and flexibleProtect validation.

Other models: Assessment / EmployeeAssessment / SubmittedAssessment / Response / Question / Organization / Notification / Tooltip
- Each model describes assessment structure, question types, responses, and submission snapshots. Review files in src/models to see schema fields and indexes. These define how controllers persist assessment and response data and are critical to map to frontend payloads.

7 — Middlewares (what they do)
- src/middlewares/auth.middleware.js
  - protect: requires Authorization: Bearer <token>; verifies JWT; populates req.user.
  - flexibleProtect: attempts session token (Authorization or cookie accessToken) then falls back to invitation token (x-invite-token header or cookie). If invite token valid and DB invitation found, sets req.guest and req.employee.
  - restrictTo(...roles): returns middleware to restrict endpoint to given roles (compares req.user.role).

- src/middlewares/employee.middleware.js
  - employeeAccess: for employee/no-login flow. Accepts token via x-invite-token, req.params.token or query.token. Verifies JWT, finds Invitation record (token or token1), checks used and expiry, attaches req.employee.

- src/middlewares/multer.middleware.js
  - upload: multer disk storage to OS temp dir or /tmp on Vercel.
  - Valid mime types: image/png, image/jpeg, image/jpg, Excel types.
  - Image size limits: MIN_SIZE = 10KB, MAX_SIZE = 4MB. validateImageSize middleware checks lower bound.
  - excelUpload: multer config for Excel uploads (no size limit).

- src/middlewares/csvUpload.middleware.js
  - Parses CSV uploads for bulk invitations (check this file for exact expected CSV format).

- src/middlewares/role.middleware.js
  - Role-based helper middleware (small utility).

8 — Routes & endpoints — detailed, sectioned
Base path: /api/v1

Note: where "protected" is listed, use Authorization: Bearer <JWT>. flexibleProtect allows session or invite based access. employeeAccess requires invite token.

A) Auth routes — /api/v1/auth
Purpose: user lifecycle, orgs, invitations, notifications, profile.

Core:
- POST /auth/register — create new user (admin or normal user). Auth: public.
- POST /auth/login — authenticate and get JWT. Body: { email, password }.
- POST /auth/logout — clear session cookie / server side sign-out.
- GET /auth/verify-email/:token — verify user email via token.
- POST /auth/forgot-password — send reset password email.
- GET /auth/reset-password/:token — validate reset token.
- POST /auth/reset-password — change password using reset token.
- POST /auth/change-password — change password while logged-in (protect).
- POST /auth/complete-profile — finalize initial profile after registration or invite.
- GET /auth/current-user-session — return current session details if available.
- GET /auth/organizations — list orgs user has access to (protect).
- GET /auth/organization/:name — get members of organization by name (protect).
- GET /auth/organization-filters/:name — return filter data (departments, roles) for org (protect).

Invitations:
- POST /auth/send-invitation — create/send invitation to email (protect).
- POST /auth/send-bulk-invitation — create many invitations from CSV/Excel (protect, uploadCSV middleware).
- GET /auth/invite/:token — accept invitation (guest flow).
- GET /auth/invitation-details/:token — preview invitation details (public).
- GET /auth/invitations — list invitations (protect).
- DELETE /auth/invitation/:id — delete invitation (protect).
- DELETE /auth/reset-assessment/:id — reset assessment for a given invitation/employee (protect).

Profile & Notifications:
- GET /auth/me — returns user or guest info (flexibleProtect).
- GET /auth/my-profile — profile details (flexibleProtect).
- PATCH /auth/update-profile — update profile fields & upload files (protect; upload.fields([...])).
- GET /auth/notifications — protected.
- PATCH /auth/notifications/:id/read — protected.
- PATCH /auth/notifications/read-all — protected.
- DELETE /auth/notifications/clear-all — protected.
- PATCH /auth/update-notifications — protected.

B) Assessment routes — /api/v1/assessment
Purpose: create/start/submit assessments and request analytics.

- GET /assessment/start — get data needed to start an assessment (templates, stakeholders, settings) (public).
- POST /assessment/start — create an assessment draft (protect).
- POST /assessment/:assessmentId/submit — finalize assessment (protect).
- GET /assessment/history — user’s assessment history (protect).
- GET /assessment/super-admin/stats etc. — role-specific aggregated analytics (protect).

C) Employee assessment (no-login) — /api/v1/employee-assessment
Purpose: allow invited employees to take assessment via token link without logging in.

- POST /employee-assessment/start — fetch assessment instance for tokenized employee (employeeAccess).
- POST /employee-assessment/:assessmentId/submit/:token — submit employee responses with invite token (employeeAccess).

D) Questions — /api/v1/questions
Purpose: question bank CRUD and assessment question fetching.

Admin (protected):
- GET /questions/all
- GET /questions/:id
- POST /questions/multiple
- POST /questions/clone
- POST /questions/upload
- GET /questions/template/download
- PUT /questions/reorder
- PUT /questions/:id
- DELETE /questions/organization/all
- DELETE /questions/:id

User:
- GET /questions — flexibleProtect — return questions filtered for stakeholder.

E) Responses — /api/v1/responses
Purpose: capture and retrieve responses and provide exports.

- POST /responses — save or update responses (flexibleProtect).
- GET /responses/:assessmentId — get responses for an assessment.
- GET /responses/:assessmentId/export — export individual report as Excel.
- GET /responses/organization/:orgName/export — export org-level report as Excel.

F) Dashboard — /api/v1/dashboard
Purpose: aggregated reports & exports.

Public:
- GET /dashboard/public-download
- GET /dashboard/tooltips

Protected:
- GET /dashboard/employee, /manager, /leader, /admin
- GET /dashboard/org-average
- GET /dashboard/detailed-insight
- PUT /dashboard/detailed-insight
- GET /dashboard/export-pdf — export report PDF (puppeteer)
- GET /dashboard/preview-pdf-report — preview PDF
- PUT /dashboard/release-report — release report (super admin)
- GET /dashboard/manager-team-avg
- PUT /dashboard/tooltips — update tooltips (restrictTo superadmin)

Notes: PDF/export endpoints can be resource-intensive. Consider async job queue for large reports.

G) Organization — /api/v1/organization
- GET /organization/departments
- POST /organization/departments
- DELETE /organization/departments

H) Contact — /api/v1/contact
- POST /contact — public contact form.

9 — Authentication & token behavior (details)
- JWTs signed with JWT_SECRET. User token payload includes userId, role, orgName (generateAccessToken in user model).
- protect middleware: requires Authorization header Bearer token — verifies and sets req.user.
- flexibleProtect: tries session token (Authorization or cookie accessToken), else looks for invite token (x-invite-token or cookie invitationToken); if invite token valid and Invitation found, sets req.guest/req.employee.
- employeeAccess: strict invite-mode — used for public employee flows; verifies token, finds Invitation by token or token1, ensures not used and not expired, attaches req.employee.

Security considerations:
- Keep JWT_SECRET safe. Tokens expire (middleware handles TokenExpiredError).
- Invitation tokens in URL are easy to leak — prefer token in header for sensitive flows.
- Add rate-limiting to auth endpoints to mitigate brute-force.
- Validate input payloads robustly in controllers (if not present, add express-validator or Joi).

10 — File uploads & exports
- multer (diskStorage) writes temporary files to:
  - OS temp dir locally (os.tmpdir())
  - /tmp on Vercel (process.env.VERCEL ? "/tmp" : os.tmpdir())
- Allowed upload mime types:
  - Images: image/png, image/jpeg, image/jpg
  - Excel: application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet (.xlsx), application/vnd.ms-excel (.xls)
- Image size limits: min 10KB, max 4MB.
- excelUpload has no size limit (used for bulk import).
- After upload, controllers should move files to cloud (Cloudinary, S3) or process them and delete temp files.
- Exports:
  - Excel generation uses exceljs / xlsx / json2xls
  - PDF generation uses puppeteer + pdf-lib; running puppeteer in serverless requires special build packs and /tmp availability for chromium; check @sparticuz/chromium usage.

11 — Cron & DB maintenance
- src/index.js sets up a cron schedule '* * * * *' to delete expired unverified users every minute (runs only when index.js is executed, i.e., not on serverless unless you run a persistent worker).
- index.js contains a local-only DB cleanup: it attempts to drop an index named invitationId_1 from the 'assessments' collection if present. This runs only in the connect promise path and logs result. IMPORTANT: ensure this code is safe to run against any DB you use — it is intended as local fix and should not run on production without review.

12 — Deployment notes (Vercel)
- src/index.js contains an early return if process.env.VERCEL is truthy — it will not call app.listen. For serverless deployment on Vercel, app is exported and serverless functions handle requests.
- Cron and index cleanup will not run on Vercel (serverless). If cron is required in production, move tasks to a separate worker or scheduled job (e.g., Chron job on server or worker on Heroku, a scheduled function, or use GitHub Actions/Cron job).
- Puppeteer usage on Vercel needs a compatible chromium binary (the repo uses @sparticuz/chromium which helps). Test PDF endpoints in the deployed environment.

13 — Testing & QA recommendations
- Create Postman/Insomnia collection with:
  - Auth flows (register, login, get token)
  - Invite flows (send-invitation, invite acceptance, employee flow)
  - Assessment flows (create start, submit)
  - File upload flows (profile update, bulk invite)
- Add unit/integration tests for:
  - auth middleware behavior (protect, flexibleProtect, employeeAccess)
  - invitation lifecycle (create, expire, used)
  - response submit + export
- Add CI (GitHub Actions) to run linter and tests.

14 — Onboarding checklist for successor (priority)
- Populate .env from .env.example with test MongoDB & JWT secret.
- npm install & npm run dev — run health check.
- Register a test admin and validate login flow.
- Verify DB connection is successful and understand where DB is hosted.
- Create sample invitation and run employee assessment flow (start and submit).
- Test file uploads and export endpoints locally (Excel & PDF).
- Review controllers for external provider usage (which email provider, cloudinary config).
- Safeguard index cleanup: examine index-drop code in src/index.js; remove or guard it for prod.
- Create Postman collection and add docs/API.md to repo.
- Add rate limiting and input validation if missing on auth endpoints.

15 — Common issues & troubleshooting
- MongoDB connect errors: ensure MONGODB_URL is correct, check IP whitelist / SRV records. If you get 'querySrv ECONNREFUSED' locally, the repo sets DNS servers in non-production to Google (see src/index.js).
- Tokens invalid/expired: verify JWT_SECRET matches the one used to sign tokens.
- Invitation not found: verify token field looked up is token or token1 (DB may store alternate token field). employeeAccess checks both.
- Upload failures on Vercel: ensure /tmp is used and that temp files are handled after processing; cloudinary credentials required for persistent storage.
- Large export timeouts: large org exports may take long and time out; use background jobs and provide status endpoints if needed.

16 — Suggested immediate improvements (recommended)
- Add .env.example and README/API.md with these docs.
- Add OpenAPI/Swagger specification and a Postman collection.
- Move heavy exports & PDF generation to queued background workers for scalability.
- Add rate-limiting & request validation to auth endpoints.
- Audit npm dependencies and run npm audit; update critical vulnerabilities.
- Add tests for critical logic (auth, invite, response save/exports).

